dismissalComment.html: caught behind! Toe-end of the bat as he goes for the pull shot and Bangladesh have a vital breakthrough at a great time. The angle from round the wicket means Hope is always hitting against it, and it might just have kept a little lower than he expected. Looked good for a third hundred in four ODIs, but he has to walk back now.

dismissalText.commentary: Jason Holder c †Mushfiqur Rahim b Mashrafe Mortaza 62 (76b 3x4 1x6 85m) SR: 81.57

dismissalComment.html: caught behind again! He didn't begin the day very well, but he's ending it #LikeABoss! This round the wicket angle is working a treat. Keeps cramping the right-handers. And on the odd occasion he takes the ball across them, they keep playing horizontal bat shots and nicking behind. Hope fell to the pull, Holder falls to the cut. West Indies have been poor in executing their big shots this innings. #Bizarre

commentPreTextItems.html: Sabbir is on strike finally, with just one run needed.

commentTextItems.html: bouncer down the leg side, and Sabbir ducks even though he's well away from the firing line. It's called wide, and that completes Bangladesh's win

commentPostTextItems.html: 6.23pm And that brings our coverage to an end. Hope you've enjoyed the game. There's the dead rubber game coming up day after, between Ireland and Bangladesh, and after that the final. Be sure to keep joining us, and keep sending in your comments. Until next time, goodbye!

Mashrafe Mortaza: "The way we're playing, I think we bowled really well. Didn't start well, but luckily we got the breakthrough. In the middle part Mustafizur bowled well, and Shakib and Miraz too. Getting to the final was the most important thing. The boys are a bit relaxed, but two matches left, and we'll go hard, and see how it goes in the final."

Jason Holder: "Still not 100% in the field. We've definitely let ourselves down with our fielding right through the tournament. We just want to improve every time we step onto the field. We were a few runs short. I'm not one to look at the end result, we need to look at the processes and tighten up in all three departments."
Mustafizur Rahman is the Player of the Match. No interview with him.

SrizanG: "@DWolfman that is a bit too harsh to say for Pollard, his experience is the most valuable asset beside fielding. Although, I agree picking him up solely on his IPL performance might not be a wise decision to make."

AnamBMDF : "Love the way BD have defeated WI today: bowling department led by Mashrafe, the captain, with crucial wickets supported by Mustafiz and spinners and during batting, it's a total team effort (all contribute significantly). If this is translated in WC, who knows what upsets are coming then? Good rehearsal for BD to face WI in the final of tri-nations trophy."
Sanyat11: "This is exactly what it should be for Bangladesh. With the dependable five and the youngsters showing no fear... Bangladesh are going with fifteen Bengal Tigers for sure. "

6.10pm Bangladesh have wrapped it up with 15 balls to spare, and they've confirmed their place in the final. A thoroughly professional chase from them, notwithstanding a couple of dismissals to uncalled-for shots. Each of their top six got to at least 20, and two of them got past the half-century mark. That's pretty much what you need when you're chasing 248. Not much of a wicket threat from any of the West Indies bowlers barring Ashley Nurse, who dismissed each of the three left-handers at the top of the order. Sheldon Cottrell seemed to get into a bit of rhythm by the end of the innings, which was a bit of a positive, but the two allrounders, Raymon Reifer and Fabian Allen, didn't have very good games at all.

dismissalText.commentary: Tamim Iqbal b Nurse 21 (23b 4x4 0x6) SR: 91.3

dismissalComment.html: bowled him! Nurse delivers the breakthrough. Tamim jumps down the track again, but this time he isn't quite to the pitch of the ball. It dips on him, and zips through with the angle. Tamim plays for turn, looking to block it hurriedly, and it sneaks through the gate and hits leg stump

dismissalText.commentary: Shakib Al Hasan c Chase b Nurse 29 (35b 3x4 0x6) SR: 82.85

dismissalComment.html: taken at short cover! He's not to the pitch of the ball, having come down the track too early and giving Nurse the opportunity to change his length, and also go tight into his pads. It's a lot shorter now, it's a lot closer now, but Shakib is committed to the shot. Goes for the drive, tries to lift it over the infield, no such luck.

dismissalText.commentary: Soumya Sarkar c Ambris b Nurse 54 (67b 4x4 2x6) SR: 80.59

dismissalComment.html: there's a neeeeervous juggle, but he takes it in the end. Ambris at short midwicket this time as another Bangladesh player mis-hits a lofted shot. Soumya wants to get under the ball, nicely tossed up outside off, and clip it over the leg side field for a couple of runs, but the ball isn't quite as full as he thinks he is. It grips. it turns. It takes a leading edge and poof. He's gone

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Mithun b Holder 43 (53b 2x4 2x6) SR: 81.13

dismissalComment.html: bowled him, Holder breaks the partnership. Lovely delivery, full but not a half-volley, and it nips in off the pitch to burst through the massive gap between bat and pad as Mithun looks for the big drive into the covers

dismissalText.commentary: Mushfiqur Rahim c Bravo b Roach 63 (73b 5x4 1x6) SR: 86.3

dismissalComment.html: oh no, that wasn't really necessary. Roach bowls this on a length, angling into the stumps, and Mushfiqur goes for the big lap-scoop. Middles it well enough, but he ends up picking out the man on the fine leg boundary
